    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-09-27T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-09-27T10:00:00-05:00" n="291"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d291">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Commission/378: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Port Said (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_RH1"
                            type="from">Remillard</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port Said</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-27T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >September 27, 1932—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 27—10:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>With reference to Department’s cable September 23, 4 p.m., <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_MMGFR1">General McCoy</persName> aboard ship <hi
                        rend="italic">Gange</hi> replies as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Before the Commission separated in Peiping it was unofficially informed
                            by the Secretary General of the League that its presence in Geneva would
                            probably be required during the discussion of its report. <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_LERB1">Lytton</persName> expects to hear from
                                <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_DSE1">Drummond</persName> on
                            arrival at Venice, September 30. In view of the fact that <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_LERB1">Lytton</persName> has just received
                            instructions from his Government to proceed to London directly and that
                            no other member of Commission will be in Geneva unless called I had
                            intended to remain at some other place in Italy or Switzerland subject
                            to call should the Commission remain in existence.</p>
                        <p>After your consideration of the foregoing I shall be glad to comply with
                            your instructions and will talk to <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHR1">Hugh Wilson</persName> from
                            Venice.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_RH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Remillard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
